00:04:42.749 --> 00:04:45.009
school geography teacher, I want

00:04:45.019 --> 00:04:47.339
to pause briefly to address a

00:04:47.339 --> 00:04:49.769
few basic but important points.

00:04:50.909 --> 00:04:54.029
The planet has a natural carbon cycle.

00:04:54.559 --> 00:04:57.929
Carbon moves through the land, the oceans,

00:04:58.209 --> 00:05:00.629
the air, and every living thing on Earth,

00:05:00.889 --> 00:05:03.799
and it has done so for millions of years.

00:05:04.489 --> 00:05:07.039
Plants and trees absorb carbon

00:05:07.039 --> 00:05:09.909
dioxide from the air and store it in

00:05:09.909 --> 00:05:12.549
their leaves, roots, and the soil.

00:05:12.979 --> 00:05:16.299
Tiny marine organisms, like plankton, also

00:05:16.299 --> 00:05:18.419
take in carbon dioxide from the water.

00:05:19.329 --> 00:05:22.149
Some carbon is also released naturally.

00:05:22.659 --> 00:05:25.829
For example, when a volcano erupts, it

00:05:25.829 --> 00:05:28.269
sends carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.

00:05:28.549 --> 00:05:30.299
Burning wood does the same.

00:05:31.229 --> 00:05:33.289
And animals, including us,

00:05:33.629 --> 00:05:36.119
good old humans, we emit carbon

00:05:36.119 --> 00:05:37.879
dioxide when we breathe out.

00:05:38.489 --> 00:05:40.929
When we die, the carbon in our bodies

00:05:41.129 --> 00:05:43.499
is also returned to the environment.

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:46.359
And for a long time, this

00:05:46.439 --> 00:05:49.169
carbon cycle was in balance.

00:05:49.729 --> 00:05:52.219
The amount of carbon dioxide released

00:05:52.239 --> 00:05:54.619
into the atmosphere was more or

00:05:54.619 --> 00:05:56.919
less equal to the amount that was

00:05:56.929 --> 00:06:00.479
absorbed by plants, oceans, and soil.

00:06:00.959 --> 00:06:03.199
But starting around the time of

00:06:03.199 --> 00:06:05.539
the Industrial Revolution, we began

00:06:05.569 --> 00:06:08.639
burning fossil fuels — coal, oil,

00:06:08.639 --> 00:06:11.378
and natural gas — and we did so

00:06:11.608 --> 00:06:14.428
and still do so on a massive scale.

00:06:15.018 --> 00:06:17.408
This, as you know, releases

00:06:17.418 --> 00:06:19.428
huge amounts of extra carbon

00:06:19.428 --> 00:06:20.978
dioxide into the atmosphere.

00:06:21.718 --> 00:06:23.958
We began emitting more CO2

00:06:24.278 --> 00:06:25.718
than the Earth could absorb.

00:06:26.188 --> 00:06:28.288
And almost every year since

00:06:28.288 --> 00:06:30.908
then, the amount has increased.

00:06:31.688 --> 00:06:35.018
So now, almost 200 years later,

00:06:35.478 --> 00:06:39.128
there are more than 3,000 gigatons

00:06:39.128 --> 00:06:41.108
of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.

00:06:41.768 --> 00:06:44.908
A gigaton is a billion metric tonnes.

00:06:45.518 --> 00:06:49.178
And if 3,000 billion tonnes of an

00:06:49.188 --> 00:06:51.838
invisible gas is hard to imagine,

00:06:52.308 --> 00:06:54.558
the key point is this: it’s an

00:06:54.608 --> 00:06:58.188
increase of 50% compared to the

00:06:58.198 --> 00:07:00.428
start of the Industrial Revolution.

00:07:01.928 --> 00:07:04.168
And this carbon dioxide in the

00:07:04.168 --> 00:07:06.396
atmosphere acts like a kind

00:07:06.396 --> 00:07:08.346
of blanket around the Earth.

00:07:08.596 --> 00:07:10.536
It traps heat from the sun, which

00:07:10.556 --> 00:07:12.546
causes global temperatures to rise.

00:07:13.086 --> 00:07:15.016
Clearly, that is a gross

00:07:15.096 --> 00:07:18.136
simplification, but it helps bring

00:07:18.136 --> 00:07:20.596
us to the next point, which is this.

00:07:21.746 --> 00:07:24.096
Given that there is all of this carbon

00:07:24.096 --> 00:07:26.796
dioxide in the atmosphere, and carbon

00:07:26.796 --> 00:07:29.886
dioxide causes global heating, and global

00:07:29.896 --> 00:07:32.996
heating is bad, what would happen if

00:07:32.996 --> 00:07:35.636
we could “remove” the carbon dioxide?

00:07:37.066 --> 00:07:39.176
This is the principle behind

00:07:39.246 --> 00:07:42.256
carbon removal: to work on removing

00:07:42.266 --> 00:07:44.469
carbon dioxide from the planet.

00:07:45.086 --> 00:07:47.006
So, what's happening?

00:07:47.006 --> 00:07:49.746
What does carbon removal actually involve?

00:07:49.986 --> 00:07:52.256
And how does one go about removing

00:07:52.266 --> 00:07:54.296
carbon dioxide from the atmosphere?

00:07:55.166 --> 00:07:57.106
Well, the good news is

00:07:57.106 --> 00:07:58.346
that we know how to do it.

00:07:59.276 --> 00:08:02.676
The bad news is that it’s hard, expensive,

00:08:02.996 --> 00:08:05.676
and still in its very early stages.

00:08:07.056 --> 00:08:09.656
Broadly speaking, carbon removal

00:08:09.656 --> 00:08:12.466
technologies aim to do exactly what

00:08:12.476 --> 00:08:15.626
trees and oceans do naturally: take in

00:08:15.686 --> 00:08:18.706
carbon dioxide and store it somewhere

00:08:18.706 --> 00:08:20.816
safe and out of the atmosphere.

00:08:22.106 --> 00:08:25.376
Some approaches aim to speed up natural

00:08:25.376 --> 00:08:27.566
processes like mineral weathering,

00:08:27.786 --> 00:08:30.566
where rocks slowly react with carbon

00:08:30.566 --> 00:08:33.586
dioxide and trap it in solid form.

00:08:34.386 --> 00:08:36.556
Others are more technological;

00:08:36.826 --> 00:08:38.886
machines that literally suck

00:08:39.166 --> 00:08:41.036
carbon dioxide directly out of

00:08:41.046 --> 00:08:43.106
the air and store it underground.

00:08:43.826 --> 00:08:46.816
Some store carbon in soil or plants,

00:08:46.986 --> 00:08:49.546
others inject it into rock formations,

00:08:49.776 --> 00:08:52.736
and a few even store it in the ocean.

00:08:54.276 --> 00:08:56.906
One of the most talked-about is something

00:08:56.906 --> 00:09:00.236
called direct air capture, where large

00:09:00.256 --> 00:09:03.166
machines act like giant air filters,

00:09:03.625 --> 00:09:07.275
pulling in huge volumes of air and using

00:09:07.275 --> 00:09:10.775
chemical processes to extract the CO2.

00:09:11.565 --> 00:09:13.725
Once it’s captured, the carbon is

00:09:13.755 --> 00:09:16.995
compressed and injected deep underground,

00:09:17.155 --> 00:09:19.365
where it can stay for thousands of years.

00:09:20.445 --> 00:09:23.335
Then there’s this thing called enhanced

00:09:23.355 --> 00:09:25.832
weathering, where crushed rocks are

00:09:25.862 --> 00:09:28.882
spread onto farmland or coastlines.

00:09:29.552 --> 00:09:32.182
These rocks naturally react with

00:09:32.192 --> 00:09:34.852
carbon dioxide in the air or water,

00:09:35.332 --> 00:09:37.222
forming stable compounds that

00:09:37.232 --> 00:09:38.672
are eventually washed into the

00:09:38.692 --> 00:09:41.979
ocean and stored as bicarbonate.

00:09:43.092 --> 00:09:45.372
Another promising method is something

00:09:45.372 --> 00:09:48.512
called biomass carbon removal and storage.

00:09:49.512 --> 00:09:52.202
This includes things like burning plant

00:09:52.232 --> 00:09:55.132
waste to generate energy, capturing the

00:09:55.132 --> 00:09:57.682
carbon that’s released, and storing it

00:09:57.772 --> 00:10:00.742
underground, essentially closing the loop.

00:10:01.492 --> 00:10:04.212
There are other approaches too: turning

00:10:04.252 --> 00:10:07.412
biomass into bio-oil and injecting it

00:10:07.432 --> 00:10:10.029
underground, using chemical processes

00:10:10.072 --> 00:10:11.952
in the ocean to increase its carbon

00:10:11.952 --> 00:10:15.722
absorption, or even sinking agricultural

00:10:15.722 --> 00:10:18.002
waste to the bottom of oxygen-poor

00:10:18.012 --> 00:10:20.652
seas, where it breaks down very slowly

00:10:20.652 --> 00:10:23.152
and locks away carbon in sediment.

00:10:24.072 --> 00:10:26.592
It all sounds promising in theory,

00:10:27.142 --> 00:10:30.242
and even in practice, most of these

00:10:30.242 --> 00:10:32.642
technologies work pretty well.

00:10:33.332 --> 00:10:35.252
But there is a problem.

00:10:35.922 --> 00:10:39.002
They are still expensive, and as of

00:10:39.012 --> 00:10:41.682
now, they haven’t been deployed anywhere

00:10:41.712 --> 00:10:44.352
close to the scale that is required.

00:10:45.452 --> 00:10:49.492
To remove just 1% of global annual

00:10:49.502 --> 00:10:52.102
emissions, we’d need to capture around

00:10:52.102 --> 00:10:55.472
400 million tonnes of CO₂ per year.

00:10:56.302 --> 00:10:59.042
Today, the total removed by these

00:10:59.072 --> 00:11:01.782
carbon removal technologies is only

00:11:02.002 --> 00:11:04.702
about 2 million tonnes — that’s

00:11:04.892 --> 00:11:09.252
just 0.005% of global emissions.

00:11:09.882 --> 00:11:12.012
In other words, we’re only half

00:11:12.072 --> 00:11:15.405
a percent of the way to just 1%.

00:11:16.562 --> 00:11:19.512
And carbon removal is a classic

00:11:19.522 --> 00:11:22.162
victim of the chicken and egg problem.

00:11:23.192 --> 00:11:25.072
Because there aren’t many customers,

00:11:25.402 --> 00:11:27.942
the cost of carbon removal is still

00:11:27.952 --> 00:11:30.209
very high, often many hundreds

00:11:30.209 --> 00:11:32.349
of dollars per tonne of CO2.

00:11:33.209 --> 00:11:34.769
And because the cost is high,

00:11:35.199 --> 00:11:36.619
there aren’t many customers.

00:11:37.859 --> 00:11:40.276
In other words, it’s hard to lower the

00:11:40.296 --> 00:11:43.296
cost without customers, but hard to

00:11:43.306 --> 00:11:46.086
get customers when the cost is so high

00:11:47.106 --> 00:11:50.456
But history is full of examples

00:11:50.596 --> 00:11:52.446
where this cycle was broken.

00:11:53.364 --> 00:11:54.824
The first computers were

00:11:54.834 --> 00:11:57.324
massive and cost millions.

00:11:57.644 --> 00:11:59.924
The first hard drives could store

00:11:59.954 --> 00:12:02.884
a few megabytes but cost a fortune.

00:12:03.554 --> 00:12:05.734
Vaccines, solar panels,

00:12:06.114 --> 00:12:08.624
smartphones–they all started out

00:12:08.654 --> 00:12:11.884
very expensive, slow, and niche.

00:12:12.504 --> 00:12:16.474
But as technology improved and demand

00:12:16.544 --> 00:12:20.094
grew, prices fell dramatically.

00:12:21.194 --> 00:12:23.254
In the case of solar panels,

00:12:23.544 --> 00:12:27.666
the cost has fallen by 99.6%

00:12:27.764 --> 00:12:29.244
since they were first developed.

00:12:30.244 --> 00:12:32.754
